The following was written by the late Douglas Adams of "Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy" fame.
"Australia is a very confusing place, taking up a large amount of the bottom half of the planet. It is recognisable from orbit because of many unusual features, including what at first looks like an enormous bite taken out of its southern edge; a wall of sheer cliffs which plunge into the girting sea.
Geologists assure us that this is simply an accident of geomorphology, but they still call it the "Great Australian Bight", proving that not only are they covering up a more frightening theory but they can't spell either.
The first of the confusing things about Australia is the status of the place. Where other landmasses and sovereign lands are classified as continent, island or country, Australia is considered all three.
Typically, it is unique in this.
The second confusing thing about Australia is the animals. They can be divided into three categories: Poisonous, Odd, and Sheep. It is true that of the 10 most poisonous arachnids on the planet, Australia has 9 of them. Actually, it would be more accurate to say that of the 9 most poisonous arachnids, Australia has all of them.
Any visitors should be careful to check inside boots (before putting them on), under toilet seats (before sitting down) and generally everywhere else.
A stick is very useful for this task.
The last confusing thing about Australia is the inhabitants.
A short history: Sometime around 40,000 years ago some people arrived in boats from the north. They ate all the available food, and a lot of them died.
The ones who survived learned respect for the balance of nature, man's proper place in the scheme of things, and spiders. They settled in and spent a lot of the intervening time making up strange stories.  They also discovered a stick that kept coming back.
Then, around 200 years ago, Europeans arrived in boats from the north.
More accurately, European convicts were sent, with a few deranged people in charge. They tried to plant their crops in autumn (failing to take account of the reversal of the seasons), ate all their food, and a lot of them died.
About then the sheep arrived, and have been treasured ever since. It is interesting to note here that the Europeans always consider themselves vastly superior to any other race they encounter, since they can lie, cheat, steal and litigate (marks of a civilised culture they say), whereas all the Aboriginals can do is happily survive being left in the middle of a vast red-hot desert - equipped with a stick.
Eventually, the new lot of people stopped being Europeans on 'extended holiday' and became Australians. The changes are subtle, but deep, caused by the mind-stretching expanses of nothingness and eerie quiet, where a person can sit perfectly still and look deep inside themselves to the core of their essence, their reasons for being, and the necessity of checking inside their boots every morning for fatal surprises. They also picked up the most finely tuned sense of irony in the world, and the Aboriginal gift for making up stories. Be warned.
There is also the matter of the beaches. Australian beaches are simply the nicest and best in the world, although anyone actually venturing into the sea will have to contend with sharks, stinging jellyfish, stonefish (a fish which sits on the bottom of the sea, pretends to be a rock and has venomous barbs sticking out of its back that will kill just from the pain) and surfboarders. However, watching a beach sunset is worth the risk.
As a result of all this hardship, dirt, thirst and wombats, you would expect Australians to be a sour lot. Instead, they are genial, jolly, cheerful and always willing to share a kind word with a stranger. Faced with insurmountable odds and impossible problems, they smile disarmingly and look for a stick. Major engineering feats have been performed with sheets of corrugated iron, string and mud.
Alone of all the races on earth, they seem to be free from the 'Grass is greener on the other side of the fence' syndrome, and roundly proclaim that Australia is, in fact, the other side of that fence. They call the land "Oz" or "Godzone" (a verbal contraction of "God's Own Country"). The irritating thing about this is... they may be right.
TIPS TO SURVIVING AUSTRALIA
Don't ever put your hand down a hole for any reason - WHATSOEVER.
The beer is stronger than you think, regardless of how strong you think it is.
Always carry a stick.
Air-conditioning is imperative.
Do not attempt to use Australian slang unless you are a trained linguist and extremely good in a fist fight.
Wear thick socks.
Take good maps. Stopping to ask directions only works when there are people nearby.
If you leave the urban areas, carry several litres of water with you at all times, or you will die. And don't forget a stick.
Even in the most embellished stories told by Australians, there is always a core of truth that it is unwise to ignore.
HOW TO IDENTIFY AUSTRALIANS
They pronounce Melbourne as "Mel-bin".
They think it makes perfect sense to decorate highways with large fibreglass bananas, prawns and sheep.
They think "Woolloomooloo" is a perfectly reasonable name for a place, that "Wagga Wagga" can be abbreviated to "Wagga", but "Woy Woy" can't be called "Woy".
Their hamburgers will contain beetroot. Apparently it's a must-have. How else do you get a stain on your shirt?
They don't think it's summer until the steering wheel is too hot to handle.
They believe that all train timetables are works of fiction.
And they all carry a stick."

We are fortunate enough to have a LOT of family close by so that is how I have been staying sane (and getting some help with my girls). Last weekend was Labor Day weekend and we always spend it with my husband's family out in the country, doing crafts, making fried pies and dove hunting (controversial I know :joy:).
Our household has started fermenting - making batches of hot sauce for friends :fire:

Some friends and I started a co-op to help each other with little building projects we have and to socialise again, first project we helped build a workshop over a couple months. Turns out I'm a pro sander!

To counter balance the various work challenges of the year, I picked up some art painting and sketching courses, then picked up trial running, well, when I say trail running.. more shuffling quickly up a hill and then letting nature and physics take over for the downward part - but the best bit is running though some lovely Galway countryside. Also saved some cute kittens that were dumped (cue - obligatory cute cat photo).

I got cracking on a project I‚Äôve been meaning to do for a while. I get a real kick out of building things with my hands and l love seeing the finished product. Final fitment this weekend!! :pencil2::triangular_ruler::hammer_and_wrench:

Hi all, what an amazing thread, auch beautiful photos!

I‚Äôve been teaching lots of Yoga (mostly online) and recorded yoga videos for our so called Healthy Living platform - a community of families in south London, so parents/carers can practice yoga and mindfulness with children from home in their own time. :woman_in_lotus_position::skin-tone-4:

For my own self care I recently (finally) started exploring the UK more (#staycation) and spent some time at the seaside with my partner and 15month old daughter. Was really good for the soul.

I‚Äôve been keeping sane by going for an evening harbour walk most days, jigsaw puzzles, and have finally started a vinyl collection, which I‚Äôm loving :heart: And I‚Äôve also been enjoying some :wine_glass: and :chocolate_bar:  ü•∞

Similar to <@UPL8C7DB7> I was never a runner pre-COVID, but lately I‚Äôve really enjoyed getting out for a coastal run a few times a week. Fresh air and sea breeze are great for stress relief. We are so lucky to live in such a beautiful city :ocean::sunny:

I think my team would know that pre COVID I would be the last person to ever wake up to go for a walk/jog or walk home from the office (40 min walk) :see_no_evil: In fact my status on uber was at platinum level! Proud to say I‚Äôve stayed clear of ubers and have started the bay walk at least 2 times a week :raised_hands:Great way to unwind after a long day and the amazing view keeps you walking:woman-running::woman-running::sunrise::sunrise:

I would be lying if I said :wine_glass: and :chocolate_bar: hadn't helped keep me sane at times :flushed: but like many of you, my refuge is outdoors.  Here is one of my favourite walks which is less than 30 mins round trip from my apartment (so easy to fit in between meetings... although I still don't do it enough!).  Fresh air, sunshine and good tunes makes any day brighter. :sunny: :yellow_heart:

I haven't learned a new skill like you impressive bunch but I have been spending lots of quality time with my family who moved from Qld just in time for the borders to close, this photo of my nephew and me (obvs!)  was taken last week on our family get away to Byron :sunglasses:

I learnt how to sew on YouTube during lockdown and I permanently borrowed my mother‚Äôs sewing machine. So far, I have created lots of clothing for myself (t-shirts, pjs, underwear, button up shirts, shorts, face masks). It‚Äôs an incredibly soothing creative process to make everything and very grateful to have acquired this new skill.

I've been getting out of the house for a walk at lunchtime (anyone else in the St George area who wants to join me ?), mountain bike riding as well as getting into some hobbies that I have not had a lot of time for including spending some time in my man-cave exploring my inner engineer/geek...

This is such an inspiring thread! Like many of you, time in nature and with family has been a sanity saver for me this year. It‚Äôs also a reminder to be grateful for the beautiful part of the world we live in, especially while we‚Äôre stuck here :wink:. We loved our city walks and swims, and once we were allowed to travel within the state, we took advantage with a bunch of road trips and mini breaks. My kids also highly recommended sliding on mudflats for a stress release, but they don‚Äôt do the laundry :eyes:!

Karate has been my (family) go to activity ..... went from normal to Zoom and back to a level of normalcy with limited student classes.....plus my wife has reluctantly joined the father / daughter thing, I have tried to convince her sparring is not a way to settle domestic difference of opinion :grin: she has a different opinion on that :smiley: ......plus the iso veges are still alive
I've painted some mini pots for my plants during this time. Some are recycled from food packages. It brings more colors to my balcony.

Cooking, gardening and meditation (most importantly) is keeping me stay positive.  My cooking pictures are posted on Instagram - lataskitchenanicca  - ping me if you need recipes for any :slightly_smiling_face:
I have volunteered with Redcross to call people who live alone each morning since lockdown, it only takes 5 mins most time but the happiness tone form the other end really makes my day.

Here is one a bit different :smile: Rather than spending all my weekends not social distancing with all my mates at the pub, I had time to tick off something I have been wanting to achieve for awhile: got my recreational pilot licence! :airplane:
Every Saturday I help out at my partner's cafe and enjoy making hundreds of cups of coffee. Get to talk to the regulars and they always have interesting stories :blush:
:awesome:
A bit of early morning indoor climbing, gets me out of the house and challenges the mind and body!

I send these pics to my team & as a benefit I now have a series of sunrise shots covering the changing light of March to September :frame_with_picture:

I had always meant to take photos from my phone or social media and make them into something (but never had time).  We unfortunately had Covid visit our house (for a brief period thankfully) but it gave me the kick I needed to create something that we can all look at every day, to remind us of the fun experiences we used to have before things got a bit crazy.

I created this wall of gratitude and pass it every time I grab a coffee, or when we sit down to eat. It makes me grateful for what we still have, and gives me something to look forward to when we can travel again so I can add more memories!  <#C0106J18E06|stayingsocial>
